[{"location":"theory/#Permittivity","page":"Theory","title":"Permittivity","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"In electromagnetism, the permittivity is a measure of the electric polarizability of a dielectric.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The polarizability usually refers to the tendency of matter, when subjected to an electric field, to acquire an electric dipole moment in proportion to that applied field. It is a property of all matter, inasmuch as matter is made up of elementary particles which have an electric charge, namely protons and electrons. When subject to an electric field, the negatively charged electrons and positively charged atomic nuclei are subject to opposite forces and undergo charge separation.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The electric susceptibility (chi_texte) is a dimensionless proportionality constant that indicates the degree of polarization of a dielectric material in response to an applied electric field. The greater the electric susceptibility, the greater the ability of a material to polarize in response to the field, and thereby reduce the total electric field inside the material (and store energy).","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/#Definition-for-linear-dielectrics","page":"Theory","title":"Definition for linear dielectrics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"If a dielectric material is a linear, homogeneous and isotropic material with \"instantaneous\" response to changes in electric field, then the electric susceptibility is defined as the constant of proportionality relating an electric field mathbfE to the induced dielectric polarization density mathbfP such that:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbfP = varepsilon_0 chi_mathrme mathbfE","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbfP is the nduced dielectric polarization density,\nvarepsilon_0 is the electric permittivity of free space (electric constant),\nchi_mathrme is the electric susceptibility,\nmathbfE is the electric field.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The susceptibility is related to its relative permittivity (dielectric constant) varepsilon_textrmr by","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"chi_texte = varepsilon_textrmr - 1","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"so in the case of a vacuum chi_textrme =  0.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"In electromagnetism, the electric displacement field mathbfD represents the distribution of electric charges in a given medium resulting from the presence of an electric field mathbfE, which is related to the polarization density mathbfP by the following relation:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbfD = varepsilon_0mathbfE + mathbfP = varepsilon_0 (1 + chi_textrme) mathbfE = varepsilon_textrmr varepsilon_0 mathbfE = varepsilonmathbfE","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"varepsilon = varepsilon_textrmr varepsilon_0 is the permittivity,\nvarepsilon_textrmr = (1+chi_textrme)  is the relative permittivity.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/#Nonlinear/anisotropic-susceptibility","page":"Theory","title":"Nonlinear/anisotropic susceptibility","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"In many materials the polarizability starts to saturate at high values of electric field. This saturation can be modelled by a nonlinear susceptibility. These susceptibilities are important in nonlinear optics and lead to effects such as second-harmonic generation (such as used to convert infrared light into visible light, in green laser pointers).","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The standard definition of nonlinear susceptibilities in SI units is via a Taylor expansion of the polarization's reaction to electric field:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":" P = P_0 + varepsilon_0 chi^(1) E + varepsilon_0 chi^(2) E^2 + varepsilon_0 chi^(3) E^3 + cdots","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"(Except in ferroelectric materials, the built-in polarization is zero, P_0 = 0.) The first susceptibility term, chi^(1), corresponds to the linear susceptibility described above. While this first term is dimensionless, the subsequent nonlinear susceptibilities chi^(n) have units of (mV)^n1.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The nonlinear susceptibilities can be generalized to anisotropic materials in which the susceptibility is not uniform in every direction. In these materials, each susceptibility chi^(n) becomes an (n + 1)-degree tensor. Eg: to describe anisotropic media a polarizability rank two tensor alpha is defined,","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbbalpha =\nbeginbmatrix\nalpha_xx  alpha_xy  alpha_xz \nalpha_yx  alpha_yy  alpha_yz \nalpha_zx  alpha_zy  alpha_zz \nendbmatrix","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The elements describing the response parallel to the applied electric field are those along the diagonal. A large value of alpha_yx here means that an electric-field applied in the x-direction would strongly polarize the material in the y-direction. Explicit expressions for alpha have been given for homogeneous anisotropic ellipsoidal bodies.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"Many linear dielectrics are isotropic, but it is possible nevertheless for a material to display behavior that is both linear and anisotropic, or for a material to be non-linear but isotropic. Anisotropic but linear susceptibility is common in many crystals.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"In general, permittivity is not a constant, as it can vary with the position in the medium, the frequency of the field applied, humidity, temperature, and other parameters.","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/#Molecular-polarizability","page":"Theory","title":"Molecular polarizability","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"The polarizability of an atom or molecule is defined as the ratio of its induced dipole moment mathbfP to the local electric field mathbfE; in a crystalline solid, one considers the dipole moment per unit cell. This parameter is the molecular polarizability (alpha), and the dipole moment resulting from the local electric field mathbfE_mathrmlocal is given by:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbfp = varepsilon_0alpha mathbfE_mathrmlocal","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"This introduces a complication however, as locally the field can differ significantly from the overall applied field. We have:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"mathbfP = N mathbfp = N varepsilon_0 alpha mathbfE_mathrmlocal","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"where mathbfP is the polarization per unit volume, and N is the number of molecules per unit volume contributing to the polarization. Thus, if the local electric field is parallel to the ambient electric field, we have:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"chi_mathrme mathbfE = N alpha mathbfE_mathrmlocal","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"Thus only if the local field equals the ambient field can we write:","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"chi_mathrme =  N alpha","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"Note that the local electric field seen by a molecule is generally different from the macroscopic electric field that would be measured externally. This discrepancy is taken into account by the Clausius–Mossotti relation (below) which connects the bulk behaviour (polarization density due to an external electric field according to the electric susceptibility chi = varepsilon_r-1) with the molecular polarizability alpha due to the local field. In some materials, the Clausius–Mossotti relation holds and reads","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"fracchi_mathrme3+chi_mathrme =  fracN alpha3","category":"page"},{"location":"theory/#Notes:","page":"Theory","title":"Notes:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"theory/","page":"Theory","title":"Theory","text":"Permittivity as a function of frequency can take on real or complex values.\nIn SI units, permittivity is measured in farads per meter (Fm or A^2 s^4 kg^1 m^3). The displacement field mathbfD is measured in units of coulombs per square meter (Cm^2), while the electric field mathbfE is measured in volts per meter (Vm).\nmathbfD and mathbfE describe the interaction between charged objects. mathbfD is related to the charge densities associated with this interaction, while mathbfE is related to the forces and potential differences.\nThe permittivity varepsilon and permeability mu of a medium together determine the phase velocity v = fraccn of electromagnetic radiation through that medium:\nvarepsilon mu = frac1v^2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/#The-Voigt-profile","page":"Voigt","title":"The Voigt profile","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voigt_profile","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"Without loss of generality, we can consider only centered profiles, which peak at zero. The Voigt profile is then","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"V(xsigmagamma) equiv int_-infty^infty G(xsigma)L(x-xgamma) dx","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"where x is the shift from the line center, G(xsigma) is the centered Gaussian profile:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"G(xsigma) equiv frace^-x^2(2sigma^2)sigma sqrt2pi","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"and L(xgamma) is the centered Lorentzian profile:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"L(xgamma) equiv fracgammapi(x^2+gamma^2)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"The defining integral can be evaluated as:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"V(xsigmagamma)=fracoperatornameRew(z)sigmasqrt2 pi","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"where operatornameRew(z) is the real part of the Faddeeva function evaluated for","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"z=fracx+igammasigmasqrt2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"source: https://scipython.com/book/chapter-8-scipy/examples/the-voigt-profile/","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"The Voigt line profile occurs in the modelling and analysis of radiative transfer in the atmosphere. It is the convolution of a Gaussian profile, G(x sigma) and a Lorentzian profile, $ L(x; \\gamma):","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"V(x sigma gamma) = int_-infty^infty G(xsigma)L(x-xgamma)mathrmdx","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"G(xsigma) = frac1sigmasqrt2piexpleft(-fracx^22sigma^2right) quad mathrmandquad L(xgamma) = fracgammapix^2 + gamma^2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"Here gamma is the half-width at half-maximum (HWHM) of the Lorentzian profile and sigma is the standard deviation of the Gaussian profile, related to its HWHM, alpha, by alpha = sigmasqrt2ln 2. In terms of frequency, nu, x = nu - nu_0 where nu_0 is the line centre.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"There is no closed form for the Voigt profile, but it is related to the real part of the Faddeeva function, w(z) by","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"V(xsigmagamma) = fracrenewcommandReoperatornameReRew(z)sigmasqrt2pi mathrmwherez = fracx + igammasigmasqrt2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"The program below plots the Voigt profile for gamma = 01, alpha = 01 and compares it with the corresponding Gaussian and Lorentzian profiles. The equations above are implemented in the three functions, G, L and V defined in the code below.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"using SpecialFunctions: erfcx\nusing Plots\ngr() # hide\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"\"\"\" The Faddeeva function \"\"\"\nw(x) = erfcx(-im*x)\n\n\"\"\" Return Gaussian line shape at x with HWHM alpha \"\"\"\nfunction G(x, alpha)\n    return sqrt(log(2) / pi) / alpha * exp(-(x / alpha)^2 * log(2))\nend\n\n\"\"\" Return Lorentzian line shape at x with HWHM gamma \"\"\"\nfunction L(x, gamma)\n    return gamma / pi / (x^2 + gamma^2)\nend\n\n\"\"\" Return the Voigt line shape at x with Lorentzian component HWHM gamma\nand Gaussian component HWHM alpha. \"\"\"\nfunction V(x, alpha, gamma)\n    sigma = alpha / sqrt(2 * log(2))\n\n    return real(w((x + im * gamma) / sigma / sqrt(2))) / sigma / sqrt(2 * pi)\n    return w((x + im * gamma) / (sigma * sqrt(2))) / (sigma * sqrt(2 * pi))\nend\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"alpha, gamma = 0.1, 0.1\n\nxx = LinRange(-0.8, 0.8, 1001)\nplot(xx, G.(xx, alpha), label=\"Gaussian\")\nplot!(xx, L.(xx, gamma), label=\"Lorentzian\")\nplot!(xx, V.(xx, alpha, gamma), label=\"Voigt\")","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"alpha, gamma = 0.1, 0.1\n\nxx = LinRange(-0.8, 0.8, 1001)\nplot(xx, G.(xx, alpha), label=\"Gaussian\")\nplot!(xx, L.(xx, gamma), label=\"Lorentzian\")\nplot!(xx, V.(xx, alpha, gamma), label=\"Voigt\")","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"In the limiting cases of sigma=0 and gamma=0 then V(xsigmagamma) simplifies to L(xgamma) and G(xsigma), respectively.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"b_list = [.2 .4 .8]\nalpha′, gamma′ = b_list * alpha, (1 .- b_list) * gamma\n\nxx = LinRange(-0.8, 0.8, 1001)\nplot(xx, G.(xx, alpha), label=\"Gaussian\")\nplot!(xx, L.(xx, gamma), label=\"Lorentzian\")\nplot!(xx, V.(xx, alpha′, gamma′), label=[\"Voigt b=$b\" for b in b_list])","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/#Properties","page":"Voigt","title":"Properties","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"The Voigt profile is normalized:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"  int_-infty^infty V(xsigmagamma)dx = 1","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"since it is a convolution of normalized profiles. The Lorentzian profile has no moments (other than the zeroth), and so the moment-generating function for the Cauchy distribution is not defined. It follows that the Voigt profile will not have a moment-generating function either, but the characteristic function for the Cauchy distribution is well defined, as is the characteristic function for the normal distribution.  The characteristic function for the (centered) Voigt profile will then be the product of the two:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"  varphi_f(tsigmagamma) = E(e^ixt) = e^-sigma^2t^22 - gamma t","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"Since normal distributions and Cauchy distributions are stable distributions, they are each closed under convolution (up to change of scale), and it follows that the Voigt distributions are also closed under convolution.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/voigt/","page":"Voigt","title":"Voigt","text":"\"\"\" Return the Complex Voigt line shape at x with Lorentzian component HWHM gamma\nand Gaussian component HWHM alpha. \"\"\"\nfunction V_complex(x, alpha, gamma)\n    sigma = alpha / sqrt(2 * log(2))\n\n    return w((x + im * gamma) / (sigma * sqrt(2))) / (sigma * sqrt(2 * pi))\nend\n\nalpha, gamma = 0.1, 0.1\nxx = LinRange(-0.8, 0.8, 1001)\nplot(\n    plot(xx, real(V_complex.(xx, alpha, gamma)), label=\"real\"),\n    plot(xx, imag(V_complex.(xx, alpha, gamma)), label=\"imag\"),\n    layout =(2,1)\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/#Drude-model:-Driven-harmonic-oscillator","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model: Driven harmonic oscillator","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"source: Plasmonics: Fundamentals and Applications","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"One can write a simple equation of motion for an electron of the plasma sea subjected to an external electric field E:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"m ddotx + m gamma dotx = e E","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"If we assume a harmonic time dependence E(t) = E_0 e^i omega t of the driving field, a particular solution of this equation describing the oscillation of the electron is x(t) = x_0 e^i omega t. The complex amplitude x_0 incorporates any phase shifts between driving field and response via","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"x(t) = fracem (omega^2 + i gamma omega) E(t)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"The displaced electrons contribute to the macroscopic polarization P = nex, explicitly given by","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"P = -fracn e^2m(omega^2 + i gamma omega) E","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"Inserting this expression for P into equation (D = varepsilon_0 E + P) yields","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"D = varepsilon_0(1 - fracomega_p^2omega^2 + i gamma omega)E","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"where omega_p^2 = fracn e^2varepsilon_0 m is the plasma frequency of the free electron gas. Therefore we arrive at the desired result, the dielectric function of the free electron gas:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"varepsilon(omega) = 1 - fracomega_p^2omega^2 + i gamma omega","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"The real and imaginary components of this complex dielectric function varepsilon(omega) = varepsilon_1(omega) + i varepsilon_2(omega) are given by","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"varepsilon_1(omega) = 1 - fracomega_p^2 tau^21 + omega^2 tau^2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"varepsilon_2(omega) = 1 - fracomega_p^2 tauomega(1 + omega^2 tau^2)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"where we have used gamma = frac1tau.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"using Plots\ngr() # hide\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"Drude(omega, omega_p, gamma) = 1 - omega_p^2 / (omega^2 + im * gamma * omega)\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"omega = 0:.1:10\nomega_p = 1\ngamma = 1\n\neps_drude = @. Drude(omega, omega_p, gamma)\n\nplot(omega, [real(eps_drude) imag(eps_drude)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], layout=(2,1))","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"It is insightful to study (???) for a variety of different frequency regimes with respect to the collision frequency gamma. We will limit ourselves here to frequencies omega  omega_p, where metals retain their metallic character. For large frequencies close to omega_p , the product omega tau gg 1, leading to negligible damping. Here, varepsilon(omega) is predominantly real, and","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"varepsilon(omega) = 1- fracomega_p^2omega^2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"can be taken as the dielectric function of the undamped free electron plasma.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/drude/","page":"Drude model","title":"Drude model","text":"omega = 0:.1:10\nomega_p = 3\ngamma = 1\n\neps_drude = @. Drude(omega, omega_p, gamma)\neps_approx = @. 1 - omega_p^2 / omega^2\n\nplot(omega, real(eps_drude), label=\"Re(ε(ω))\", ylimits=[-10, 1])\nplot!(omega, eps_approx, label=\"approx\")","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/#Gaussian-function-(Normal-distribution)","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian function (Normal distribution)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"Gaussian functions are often used to represent the probability density function of a normally distributed random variable with expected value mu and variance sigma^2. In this case, the Gaussian is of the form:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"g(x)=frac 1sigma sqrt 2pi exp left(-frac 12frac (x-mu )^2sigma ^2right)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/#Multi-dimensional-Gaussian-function-(Multivariate-normal-distribution)","page":"Gaussian","title":"Multi-dimensional Gaussian function (Multivariate normal distribution)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"In an n-dimensional space a Gaussian function can be defined as","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"f(x) = exp(-x^TCx) ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"where x=x_1dotsx_n is a column of n coordinates, C is a [[positive-definite matrix|positive-definite]] ntimes n matrix, and ^T denotes [[transpose|matrix transposition]].","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"The integral of this Gaussian function over the whole n-dimensional space is given as","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"int_mathbbR^n exp(-x^TCx)  dx = sqrtfracpi^ndet C ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"It can be easily calculated by diagonalizing the matrix C and changing the integration variables to the eigenvectors of  C.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"More generally a shifted Gaussian function is defined as","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"f(x) = exp(-x^TCx+s^Tx) ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"where s=s_1dotss_n is the shift vector and the matrix C can be assumed to be symmetric, C^T=C, and positive-definite.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"varphi(xi x_0 gamma) =  e^i x_0 xi cdot e^- gamma xi^2","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"using Plots\ngr() # hide\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"Gaussian(x, μ, σ) = 1 / (σ * sqrt(2π)) * exp(-1/2 * (x - μ)^2 / σ^2)\n\nμ, σ = 6, .5\nX = LinRange(0,10,1001)\nplot(X, Gaussian.(X, μ, σ))","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"phi(ξ, x₀, γ) = exp(- im * x₀ * ξ) * exp(-(γ * ξ)^2)\n\nΞ = LinRange(-2π, 2π, 1001)\nplot(Ξ, phi.(Ξ, μ, σ))","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/gaussian/","page":"Gaussian","title":"Gaussian","text":"plot(Ξ, abs.(phi.(Ξ, μ, σ)))","category":"page"},{"location":"composite/#Models-with-arbitrary-accuracy","page":"Composites","title":"Models with arbitrary accuracy","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"composite/","page":"Composites","title":"Composites","text":"MultiPoleDebyeModel\nMultiLorentzPoleModel","category":"page"},{"location":"composite/#Permittivity.MultiPoleDebyeModel","page":"Composites","title":"Permittivity.MultiPoleDebyeModel","text":"MultiPoleDebyeModel(eps_inf, sigma, eps, tau)\n\nThe multi-pole Debye model with static conductivity:\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty  + sum limits_i^N fracDeltavarepsilon_i1 + j omega tau_i + fracsigma_sj omega varepsilon_0\n\nwhere\n\nsigma_s the static conductivity\nDeltavarepsilon_i is the change in permittivity due to the ith dispersion\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"composite/#Permittivity.MultiLorentzPoleModel","page":"Composites","title":"Permittivity.MultiLorentzPoleModel","text":"MultiLorentzPoleModel(eps_inf, eps, omega_p, delta)\n\nThe Drude model in combination with multiple Lorentz oscillator poles:\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty  + sum limits_N fracDeltavarepsilon omega_p^2omega_p^2 - omega(omega + j 2delta)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"composite/","page":"Composites","title":"Composites","text":"PermittivityTable","category":"page"},{"location":"composite/#Permittivity.PermittivityTable","page":"Composites","title":"Permittivity.PermittivityTable","text":"PermittivityTable(omega, eps)\n\nInterpolate values between tabulated data points.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Models","page":"Models","title":"Models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"model/","page":"Models","title":"Models","text":"DielectricConstant\nDielectricModel\nDebyeModel\nColeColeModel\nColeDavidson\nHavriliakNegamiModel\nFreeElectronPlasmaModel\nDrudeModel\nLorentzModel","category":"page"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.DielectricConstant","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.DielectricConstant","text":"DielectricConstant(eps_inf)\n\nThe dielectric constant:\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty\n\nwhere varepsilon can be real or complex value.\n\nExample\n\neps_inf = 5.\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = DielectricConstant(eps_inf)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.DielectricModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.DielectricModel","text":"DielectricModel(eps_inf, sigma)\n\nThe dielectric model includes perfect (lossless) dielectrics, conductive (lossy) materials, and perfect electric conductors.\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty + fracsigmaomega varepsilon_0\n\nExample\n\nusing Plots\nplotlyjs()\n\nusing Permittivity\n\nusing PhysicalConstants.CODATA2018: ε_0\nusing Unitful: ustrip\n\neps_inf = 5.\nsigma = 1. * ustrip(ε_0)\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = DielectricModel(eps_inf, sigma)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.DebyeModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.DebyeModel","text":"DebyeModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau)\n\nThe Debye relaxation is the dielectric relaxation response of an ideal, noninteracting population of dipoles to an alternating external electric field. It can also describes the relaxation of atomic vibrations.\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty  + fracvarepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty1 + j omega tau\n\nwhere\n\nvarepsilon_s is a static (low frequency) dielectric permittivity,\nvarepsilon_infty is permittivity at high frequency limit (optical permittivity),\ntau = frac1omega_r is the characteristic relaxation time,\nomega_r is relaxation frequency.\n\nSeparating into the real part varepsilon and the imaginary part varepsilon of the complex dielectric permittivity yields:\n\nbeginalign*\n    varepsilon = varepsilon_infty + fracvarepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty1 + omega^2 tau^2 \n    varepsilon = frac(varepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty) omega tau1 + omega^2 tau^2\nendalign*\n\nExample\n\nusing Plots # hide\n\neps_s = 10.\neps_inf = 5.\ntau = 1.\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = DebyeModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10);\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.ColeColeModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.ColeColeModel","text":"ColeColeModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, alpha)\n\nThe Cole–Cole equation is a relaxation model that is often used to describe dielectric relaxation in polymers.\n\nThe complex dielectric constant is given by the equation\n\nvarepsilon(omega) = varepsilon_infty + fracvarepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty1 + (j omegatau)^alpha\n\nwhere\n\nvarepsilon_s and varepsilon_infty are the \"static\" and \"infinite frequency\" dielectric constants,\nomega is the angular frequency,\ntau is a time constant and\nalpha is the exponent parameter.\n\nThe exponent parameter alpha, which takes a value between 0 and 1, allows the description of different spectral shapes. When alpha=1, the Cole-Cole model reduces to the Debye model. When alpha0, the relaxation is ''stretched''. That is, it extends over a wider range on a logarithmic omega scale than Debye relaxation.\n\nExample\n\neps_s = 10.\neps_inf = 5.\ntau = 1.\nalpha = 0.8\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = ColeColeModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, alpha)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.ColeDavidson","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.ColeDavidson","text":"ColeDavidson(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, beta)\n\nThe Cole-Davidson relaxation is an empirical modification of the Debye relaxation model in electromagnetism.\n\nvarepsilon(omega) = varepsilon_infty + fracvarepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty(1 + j omega tau)^beta\n\nwhere\n\nvarepsilon_infty is the permittivity at the high frequency limit,\nvarepsilon_s is the static, low frequency permittivity,\ntau is the characteristic relaxation time of the medium and\nbeta paramteres of the asymmetry.\n\nExample\n\neps_s = 10.\neps_inf = 5.\ntau = 1.\nbeta = 0.6\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = ColeDavidson(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, beta)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.HavriliakNegamiModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.HavriliakNegamiModel","text":"HavriliakNegamiModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, alpha, beta)\n\nThe Havriliak–Negami relaxation is an empirical modification of the Debye relaxation model in electromagnetism. Unlike the Debye model, the Havriliak–Negami relaxation accounts for the asymmetry and broadness of the dielectric dispersion curve. The model was first used to describe the dielectric relaxation of some polymers, by adding two exponential parameters to the Debye equation:\n\nhatvarepsilon(omega) = varepsilon_infty + fracvarepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty(1 + (jomegatau)^alpha)^beta\n\nwhere\n\nvarepsilon_infty is the permittivity at the high frequency limit,\nvarepsilon_s is the static, low frequency permittivity,\ntau is the characteristic relaxation time of the medium and\nalpha and beta paramteres of the broadness and asymmetry.\n\nThe terms alpha and beta are empirical parameters and their values are between 0 and 1.\n\nalpha is a damping factor (broaden the dispersion) and describes the degree of flatness of the relaxation region.\nbeta is an asymmetric factor and describes relaxation properties asymmetric around relaxation frequency\n\nDepending on application, the Fourier transform of the stretched exponential function can be a viable alternative that has one parameter less.\n\nFor beta = 1 the Havriliak–Negami equation reduces to the Cole–Cole equation, for alpha=1 to the Cole–Davidson equation.\n\nExamples\n\neps_s = 10.\neps_inf = 5.\ntau = 1.\nalpha = .8\nbeta = .6\n\nomega = exp10.(-2:.1:3)\n\nm = HavriliakNegamiModel(eps_s, eps_inf, tau, alpha, beta)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.FreeElectronPlasmaModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.FreeElectronPlasmaModel","text":"FreeElectronPlasmaModel(omega_p)\n\nThe Dielectric constant of free electron plasma:\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = 1 - fracomega_p^2omega^2\n\nExample\n\nomega_p = 5.\n\nomega = exp10.(-1:.1:2)\n\nm = FreeElectronPlasmaModel(omega_p)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.DrudeModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.DrudeModel","text":"DrudeModel(eps_inf, omega_p, gamma)\n\nThe Drude model describes intraband electron motion.\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = 1 - fracomega_p^2omega^2 + j omega gamma\n\nnote:\n\ngamma = Gamma = tau^-1\nLorentz mode wit omega_0=0\n\nExample\n\neps_inf = 5.\nomega_p = 5.\ngamma = 1.\n\nomega = exp10.(-1:.01:2)\n\nm = DrudeModel(eps_inf, omega_p, gamma)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"model/#Permittivity.LorentzModel","page":"Models","title":"Permittivity.LorentzModel","text":"LorentzModel(eps_s, eps_inf, omega_0, gamma)\n\nThe Lorentz oscillator model describes interband electron transitions.\n\nvarepsilon (omega) = varepsilon_infty + frac(varepsilon_s - varepsilon_infty) omega_0^2omega_0^2  - omega^2 - j omegaGamma\n\nExample:\n\neps_s = 10.\neps_inf = 5.\nomega_0 = 1.\ngamma = .5\n\nomega = exp10.(-1:.01:2)\n\nm = LorentzModel(eps_s, eps_inf, omega_0, gamma)\nε = m.(omega)\n\nplot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1), xaxis=:log10)\n\n@show Permittivity.eps_s(m) real(ε)[1]\n@show Permittivity.eps_inf(m) real(ε)[end]\n@show Permittivity.peak(m) maximum(imag(ε))\n\n# omega = 0.1:.01:5\n# m = LorentzModel(eps_s, eps_inf, omega_0, gamma)\n# ε = m.(omega)\n# plot(omega, [real(ε) imag(ε)], label=[\"Re(ε(ω))\" \"Im(ε(ω))\"], xlabel=\"Frequency\", layout=(2, 1))\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#Permittivity","page":"Home","title":"Permittivity","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Material-models","page":"Home","title":"Material models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Dielectrics-Materials","page":"Home","title":"Dielectrics Materials","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Dielectrics and Conductors: This includes perfect (lossless) dielectrics, conductive (lossy) materials, and perfect electric conductors.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Dielectric constant","category":"page"},{"location":"#Dispersive-Materials","page":"Home","title":"Dispersive Materials","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Dispersive (frequency-dependent) materials can correctly describe the physics behind the optical responses.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Dielectric constant of free electron gas\nDrude model: describes intraband electron motion.\nLorentz oscillator model: describes interband electron transitions.\nDebye model: describes the relaxation of atomic vibrations.\nCole–Cole model\nCole-Davidson\nHavriliak-Negami","category":"page"},{"location":"#Arbitrarily-accurate-Models","page":"Home","title":"Arbitrarily-accurate Models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The arbitrarily-accurate (albeit, perhaps unphysical) fits to experimental optical data can be obtained.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"multi-pole Debye model with static conductivity\nDrude model in combination with multiple Lorentz oscillator poles\nInterpolation of tabulated data","category":"page"},{"location":"#Nonlocal-Materials","page":"Home","title":"Nonlocal Materials","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Spatially-nonlocal effects arise when electrons are confined to small regions of space. Examples include junctions between structures, the areas around the edges of small structures, etc. These can significantly modify the electromagnetic fields, relative to classical (local) effects.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Examples","page":"Home","title":"Examples","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"julia> using Permittivity\n","category":"page"},{"location":"#Index","page":"Home","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/#Lorentz-modes:-Driven-harmonic-oscillators-with-dampening","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes: Driven harmonic oscillators with dampening","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Driven harmonic oscillators are damped oscillators further affected by an externally applied sinusoidal driving force:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"ddotx(t) + gamma dotx(t)  + omega_0^2 x(t) = A_0 e^-i omega t","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"A_0 is the driving amplitude,\nomega is the driving frequency,\nomega_0 is the undamped angular frequency,\ngamma is the damping ratio","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Lest suppose that the solution exist in the following form (gamma  0):","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"x(t) = x_0 e^-i omega_0 t e^-gamma t","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"The Lotenz-Drude term:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"fracA_0omega_0^2-omega^2-i gamma omega","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Total dielectric function:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"varepsilon(omega) = varepsilon_infty + sum limits_i fracA_iomega_i^2-omega^2-i gamma_i omega","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Note: Drude model is a special case of the Lotenz term with A_0 = omega_p^2 and omega_0 = 0","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"using Plots\ngr()\n\nLoretnz(omega, A_0, omega_0, gamma) =  A_0 / (omega_0^2 - omega^2 - im * gamma * omega)\nx(t, x_0, omega_0, gamma) = x_0 * exp(-im * omega_0 * t)* exp(-gamma * t)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"omega = 0:.01:10\n\nA_0, omega_0 = 10, 4\ngamma = [0 .25 .5 1. 2]\n\neps_lorentz = @. Loretnz(omega, A_0, omega_0, gamma)\n\nplot(\n    plot(omega, real(eps_lorentz),label=[\"γ = $g\" for g in gamma], ylims=[-6, 6]),\n    plot(omega, imag(eps_lorentz), label=[\"γ = $g\" for g in gamma]),\n    layout=(2,1)\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"t = 0:0.01:10\n\nx_0, omega_0 = 1, 1\ngamma = [0 .25 .5 1. 2]\n\nX = @. x(t, x_0, omega_0, gamma )\nplot(t, real(X))","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/#Lorentzian-lineshape-(Cauchy-distribution)","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentzian lineshape (Cauchy distribution)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"A random vector X=(X_1 ldots X_k)^T is said to have the multivariate Cauchy distribution if every linear combination of its components Y=a_1X_1+ cdots + a_kX_k has a Cauchy distribution. That is, for any constant vector ain mathbb R^k, the random variable Y=a^TX should have a univariate Cauchy distribution. The characteristic function of a multivariate Cauchy distribution is given by:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"varphi_X(t) =  e^ix_0(t)-gamma(t) ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"where x_0(t and gamma(t are real functions with x_0(t a homogeneous function of degree one and gamma(t a positive homogeneous function of degree one.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"x_0(at) = ax_0(t)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"gamma (at) = agamma (t)","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"for all t.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"An example of a bivariate Cauchy distribution can be given by:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"f(x y x_0y_0gamma)=  1 over 2 pi  left  gamma over ((x - x_0)^2 + (y - y_0)^2 +gamma^2)^32   right ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Note that in this example, even though there is no analogue to a covariance matrix, x and y are not Independence (probability theory)|statistically independent.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"We also can write this formula for complex variable. Then the probability density function of complex cauchy is :","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"f(z z_0gamma)=  1 over 2 pi  left  gamma over (z-z_0^2 +gamma^2)^32   right ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Analogous to the univariate density, the multidimensional Cauchy density also relates to the multivariate Student distribution. They are equivalent when the degrees of freedom parameter is equal to one. The density of a k dimension Student distribution with one degree of freedom becomes:","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"f(mathbf x mathbfmumathbfSigma k)= fracGammaleft(frac1+k2right)Gamma(frac12)pi^frack2leftmathbfSigmaright^frac12left1+(mathbf x-mathbfmu)^TmathbfSigma^-1(mathbf x-mathbfmu)right^frac1+k2 ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Properties and details for this density can be obtained by taking it as a particular case of the multivariate Student density.","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/#Lorentzian","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentzian","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"f(x x_0gamma)=  1 over 2 pi  left  fracgammax-x_0^2 +gamma^2  right","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"varphi(xi x_0 gamma) =  e^i x_0 xi cdot e^- gamma  xi ","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"Lorentzian(x, x₀, γ) = 1 / 2π * γ / ((x- x₀)^2 + γ^2)\n\nx₀, γ = 6, .5\nX = LinRange(0,10,1001)\nplot(X, Lorentzian.(X, x₀, γ))","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"phi(ξ, x₀, γ) = exp(- im * x₀ * ξ) * exp(-γ * abs(ξ))\n\nΞ = LinRange(-2π, 2π, 1001)\nr = phi.(Ξ, x₀, γ)\nplot(Ξ, real(r), imag(r), xlabel=\"ω\", ylabel=\"Re\", zlabel=\"Im\")","category":"page"},{"location":"appendix/lorentz/","page":"Lorentz modes","title":"Lorentz modes","text":"plot(\n    plot(Ξ, abs.(r), label=\"abs\"),\n    plot(Ξ, angle.(r), label=\"angle\"),\n    layout=(2,1)\n)","category":"page"}]
